03845nmm a2200685Ia 9780520918979DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20231998cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209189797 a10.1525/97805209189792doi  a(DE-B1597)570151  a(OCoLC)1224278182  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aPA3123b.G88 1998eb 7aLIT0041902bisacsh04a888/.01082211 aGutzwiller, Kathryn J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPoetic Garlands :bHellenistic Epigrams in Context /cKathryn J. Gutzwiller.  aReprint 2020 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2023] 4cÂ©1998  a1 online resource (420 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHellenistic Culture and Society ;v280 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEpigrams, the briefest of Greek poetic forms, had a strong appeal for readers of the Hellenistic period (323-31 B.C.). One of the most characteristic literary forms of the era, the epigram, unlike any other ancient or classical form of poetry, was not only composed for public recitation but was also collected in books intended for private reading. Brief and concise, concerned with the personal and the particular, the epigram emerged in the Hellenistic period as a sophisticated literary form that evinces the period's aesthetic preference for the miniature, the intricate, and the fragmented.Kathryn Gutzwiller offers the first full-length literary study of these important poems by studying the epigrams within the context of the poetry books in which they were originally collected. Drawing upon ancient sources as well as recent papyrological discoveries, Gutzwiller reconstructs the nature of Hellenistic epigram books and interprets individual poems as if they remained part of their original collections. This approach results in illuminating and original readings of many major poets, and demonstrates that individual epigrammatists were differentiated by gender, ethnicity, class status, and philosophical views. In an important final chapter, Gutzwiller reconstructs much of the poetic structure of Meleager's Garland, an ancient anthology of Hellenistic epigrams.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aBooks and readingxMediterranean Region. 0aBooks and readingzMediterranean Region. 0aEpigrams, GreekxHistory and criticism. 0aGreek poetry, HellenisticxHistory and criticism. 0aLiterary form. 4aAncient Archaeology. 4aAncient History. 4aNear and Middle Eastern History. 4aclassical literature. 4aethics. 4agender. 4ahistory. 4aliterature. 4amilitary history. 4amoral philosophy. 4aphilosophy. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520918979?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520918979423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520918979/original  aEBA_EMB  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles